def gini(labels):
    n=len(labels); counts={}
    for l in labels: counts[l]=counts.get(l,0)+1
    return 1 - sum((c/n)**2 for c in counts.values())
print(gini([1,1,1,1]))       # 0.0  (pure)
print(gini([0,0,1,1]))       # 0.5  (max mix)
```

Gini measures how 'mixed' a node's labels are: 0 = perfectly pure, 0.5 = maximally mixed (two classes). A decision-tree split chooses the feature and threshold that most **reduces** the weighted impurity of the child nodes — driving each branch toward purity.

```python
def gini(ls):
    n=len(ls);
    if n==0: return 0
    c={};
    for l in ls: c[l]=c.get(l,0)+1
    return 1-sum((v/n)**2 for v in c.values())
def best_split(x, y):
    parent=gini(y); best=(None,-1)
    for t in sorted(set(x)):
        L=[yi for xi,yi in zip(x,y) if xi<=t]; R=[yi for xi,yi in zip(x,y) if xi>t]
        if not L or not R: continue
        wgini=(len(L)*gini(L)+len(R)*gini(R))/len(y)
        gain=parent-wgini
        if gain>best[1]: best=(t,gain)
    return best
x=[1,2,3,10,11,12]; y=[0,0,0,1,1,1]
print(best_split(x,y))   # threshold ~3, gain 0.5 (perfect split)
```

The tree greedily picks the split with the highest information gain — here threshold 3 cleanly separates the classes (gain = full parent impurity). Recursing this on each child builds the tree; pre-pruning (max depth, min samples) stops it before it memorizes noise.
